vasive, as more industries adopt the worst workplace practices of service work. In light of these trends, we must consider the devastating effects on already vulnerable Americans because, as Gatta contends, this crisis does not need to be inevitable. Taking as a model the small percentage of "good" restaurant jobs that exist, she ultimately offers incisive commentary on what can be done to stave off this bleak future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aRestaurantsxEmployeesxRetirementzUnited States. 0aRestaurantszUnited StatesxEmployeesxEconomic conditions. 0aRestaurants. 0aRetirementxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aRetirement. 0aWorking poorxRetirementzUnited States. 0aWorking poor. 4aAmerican Dream. 4aaging. 4aeconomic security. 4ainequality. 4alow-wage work. 4apolicy. 4arestaurant work. 4aretirement. 4asavings. 4asocial security. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360741540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607415.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles